This phenomenon saw a boom after the November 2010 elections, during which 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states were added.
As a result, 180 bills restricting voting rights in 41 states were submitted only in 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of American citizenship.
Moreover, these laws limit the periods for elections in advance, nullify the right to sign up on the electoral list on the day of the elections and withdraw the right to vote for citizens with a criminal record.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. State required the voters to present a photo ID document.
The first State to introduce this request was Indiana.
The US Supreme Court confirmed the constitution of the Indian law in 2008.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this procedure to other states as well.
Over the past two years, they have supported proposals for such laws in 34 states to force voters to present identity cards with photographs.
