In fact, they do not own 11% of American citizens, i.e. 21 million people of age who are able to vote, no ID issued by the government office of their state.
Furthermore, he does not have such identity card for about five million new voters in 2012.
Moreover, the purchase of the required identity card often costs more than $100.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect mainly young, minority and low-income people.
25% African-Americans, 15% of people with income below $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 years of age and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age therefore do not have the required identity card with photos.
And that's not all.
Students who are known as voters by their inclination to democratic candidates are not entitled in several states to use their identity card with photographs issued by their schools.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who prefer Republican candidates to use cards issued by these clubs during elections.
By 2004, no state required proof of citizenship in elections.
