Moreover, they have reduced the right of persons and groups to provide assistance to voters who want to sign up.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general elections, the electoral campaign helped register some 10 million people.
However, the measures taken after 2009 caused a decrease in the registration of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
Republican legislators then adopted laws in the next five states aimed at shortening the term for elections in advance.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, the African-Americans accounted for 33% of the voters who voted in advance, even though the African-American voters in that state were only 13%.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
They formed only 11% of all voters, but 24% of the citizens voting in advance.
On the other hand, the white people, who represented 76% of all voters, accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the approval of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
