The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate disturbance last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in a mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
Furthermore, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by a standard model - our best or "at least bad" explanation of the nature and behaviour of the matter - which has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is still no 100% certainty among physicists that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle that is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data published this week during the great physical congress in Kyoto are more likely to confirm it, but all data are still missing so that we can be absolutely sure.
However, suppose it's the Higgs boson, because the risks of error appear to be small, and let's see what it is.
In this world, there is a completely indisputable law, according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be avoided - and do not try too hard, or you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that there is a similar law: Pauli's exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
It also divides physics particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we will find decent citizens, or fermions, who obediently follow Pauli's principle.
And at the other end, there are bosons, mean anarchists who don't appreciate anything - certainly not this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (by the way absolutely amazing), which is The article Adventure, in Berkeley labs: mesons that we leave unnoticed here, and "power particles" by which great natural forces spread and with which Higgs' boson is probably related in some way.
It must be said, however, that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you read this article, it is thanks to a boson with unusual banality: a photon, or "particle of light " that is the "carryer " of electromagnetic force.
When particles with an electric charge accelerate or change their direction, they "disrupt" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbing" will result in an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing but a photon - and thus one of the bosons, "power bearers."
More stable field
It's also with the Higgs boson, except that "disturb" requires a different field, the Higgs field, to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; very high energy values need to be achieved to excite it, as with the frozen surface of the pond, only a very large boulder will begin to eat.
For this reason it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator part as an accelerator in the laboratory CERN - a large hadron accelerator with friendly bundles is a circle with a circuit of 27 km! - to develop such energy.
Analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to us to clarify the relationship between Higgs and mass.
All particles and all materials are not responding to the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep itself on the fridge.
And yet, with the Higgs field, all the particles do not respond: those that do have a certain mass, while others (such as photon, let's look at it) do not.
And Mrs Nováková wonders what all these researches are for, what will they bring us?
From a scientific point of view, it is a confirmation of the validity of the standard model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any discrepancy between observation and predictions of SM.
Moreover, few physicists literally want to find them, because the slightest difference could open up the space of "new physics" and close some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge shortcomings, it does not provide any clarification of gravity (whoa!) or dark matter, which accounts for approximately 80% of space matter (whoa again!).
However, CERN has not yet discovered such contradictions.
Responses
The responses to these researches in Mr and Mrs Novak's everyday life can be very difficult to predict, but the mistake would be to think that there would be none.
Behold: at the very beginning of the 1960s, the pioneers did not have a laser in Bell's labs, nor did they have any idea of the revolution that would trigger their work.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (the previous rays were pulsed) in 1962, I have already said this - the laser was initially considered such a "toy to the lab".
Just imagine...
