In the case of Bitcoin, all network nodes are the depositary of a book of current accounts, controllers, issuers of money and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses.
However, the user may choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
The file of information relating to this transaction is electronically signed by the double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the eligibility of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that replaced bitcoins exist in the public book of current accounts distributed throughout the network.
The key phase is to write this new transaction into this book.
It takes place by solving the mathematical task assigned to computers whose solver, a temporary central banker, will have the right to complete this additional line.
This is a phase of file cutting, i.e. transforming a huge file into a shorter and unique digital fingerprint.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then "chop up" the whole.
The aim is to find a number that provides a specific print (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes will easily check its accuracy.
The transaction is then displayed indestructibly linked to the string of all other transactions; any modification would change the print.
If the user wanted to pay twice the same money in a row (within ten minutes), the network will only confirm one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned because each of them has a different fingerprint.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this remuneration is divided regularly by two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is so limited by the number of 21 million, but it can be divided into a hundred millionths, so the margin area here is...
The difficulty of the task is also increased with an increasing level of calculation.
