Difficult work in the Egyptian Constitution
President Muhammad Morsi has embarked on another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history because of the declaration of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, he decided to play the Vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of the opinion of everyone else, that the Constitutional Assembly will approve the final text the day after tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state gave the meeting another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been supplemented many times, which weakens the country's constitutional stability and leads to legal conjecture.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country's divisions.
From the opposition's point of view, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium," continues to "break his word" and" trample on justice."
However, its supporters assure that this is a means of making the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speeding up the transition process.
A referendum should take place in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the Egyptian text's purpose to clarify the article after the article.
It is also a way for the President to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while the whole country is rejecting protests.
As he confirmed in an interview for the American weekly Time, Muhammad Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
Especially because this hastily organized vote puts the Egyptian people ahead of the ultimatum: "You will either approve my text, or I will retain unlimited powers" which should otherwise end after the adoption of the new constitution.
And in this special atmosphere yesterday 85 Members of the aforementioned Constitutional Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most liberals were absent from the vote.
In the middle of November, not long before the constitution was announced, they blew up the door, not having the opportunity to assert their views.
Defenders of human rights, civil society or members of religious minorities imitated their step.
In order to reach a quorum, 11 replacements were quickly added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles of the Constitution have often been voted unanimously.
The commentators continued to pause over the fact that one of the few disputes revolved around... a prayer hour that day, when some members of the committee held that the hours in the conference room were not properly adjusted.
The text voted on last night consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, remains ultimately consistent with the 1971 version of the Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law'.
The Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the essential requirements, hoped to replace the term 'the principle' with the term 'rules', which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected represents a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
" Hypocrisy," the liberals argue, who only see it as a rhetorical problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is carried out through other articles.
In particular, they focus on Article 220, which entrusts the University of al-Azhar with an advisory role, in particular on matters relating to the control of the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to an expert on Egypt, Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "persons called to comment are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
The beginnings of theocracy can be seen in this."
The concern of liberals is even more fueled by the fact that the next university rector should be less moderate than the current one.
"There has not yet been any particular religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulama, but university workers, many of whom have studied in French schools," Alexis Blouet's moderate concern, who is preparing work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, they agree that "there may be contradictions regarding the interpretation of Article 220, because in it the terms used belong to the religious dictionary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science, notes red.].
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to comment on it".
In addition to the religious pages, the text approved yesterday is very critical of the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant restriction on the former regime.
Another controversial place: the powers vested in the military.
In accordance with the wishes of the military representatives, the verification of the defence budget will not be carried out by Parliament, but by the National Defence Council.
Furthermore, civil proceedings will not be prohibited in military courts, as requested by the Human Rights Association.
These associations speak of their doubts in relation to the text which they believe is against freedom.
The criminal act of blasphemy is preserved and the insult continues to be prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to it, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to perform in a television address last night, there are scheduled demonstrations for this afternoon.
The leaders of the state will then manifest on Saturday.
In Israel there are holy places, the belly of the world and the sea from saturated salt solution waiting for Ukrainian tourists
The promised earth combines the greatness of Bible truths, modern comfort and nature's pristineness.
AaF identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Bow to Holy Places
To visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that God's mercy will descend upon all who enter this "bath. "
And Galilee - instead of Jesus ' miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming down the storm and filling the nets.
Here, too, Jesus appeared to his disciples and after the resurrection.
But the most holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers here will walk through the Path of Pain, or Jesus Cross Way (Latin Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the Fortress of Antonio - Pretoria - where judgment took place, passes the streets of the Old Town and leads to the Temple of God's Grave on Mount Golgotha - the place of crucifixion, the stone of anointing and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian belly of the world that symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built in a place where, according to Christian legend, the tree from which they made the cross for Jesus ' crucifixion grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place for Jews - the wall of lamentations, the rest of the temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
According to tradition, people of different religions leave notes with wishes that will then be fulfilled.
Make your way through the vertical
The ruins of Masada Fortress remained from a secret hiding place from the enemy that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 B.C.E.
The ruin is located on cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who engage in climbing can get to it with their own strength.
The others will take the cable car to this historic mountain.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m there is a famous ski resort Hermon, which is experiencing a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
A shuttle bus takes tourists to this ski paradise from the foothills of the hill.
The total length of mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, the pagan gods lived on top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can't visit everyone on one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, located near Knesset (the Parliament).
It contains ancient Kumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, and approximately 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel-Aviv is also worth a visit.
In his exhibition are his screens widely represented impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akkon you can visit the Al Basha Museum, which presents to visitors several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with mannequins of spa users and spa caregivers from that time.
In Caesarea it is worth visiting the unique private museum Ralli, where you can admire the statues of Dalí and Roden.
There are no guides or souvenirs.
Admission fee is free and gifts are strictly refused.
The fifth museum - the Holocaust Museum, or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells of one of the most dramatic aspects of history.
The most tragic part of the museum - Children's Memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You walk in - and you find yourself in total darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improve Your Health
The three main spa centers of Israel are located on the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, aquaparks, delfinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, in the Red Sea you can also swim in the winter months because the water temperature in it does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius and the air is heated up to 23 degrees.
The dead sea is even warmer, and in it people bathe all year round.
The dead sea is, by the way, the strangest sea in the world, located at the lowest land point on the planet - at 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a saturated saline solution that easily maintains on the surface even people who can't swim.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Come here to undergo treatment using saltwater - brine, and medicinal mud that can treat health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to cure your nerves.
Touch the mysterious ancient past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through them passed the famous maritime road connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia.
The mention of this city is found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they shared a long and happy life.
Indeed, tourists love wandering in narrow streets named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you press against the walls of your "sign " alley, happiness will favor you.
In the Jaffa, you may encounter newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even from other countries to get their picture taken.
And in Caesarea - King Herod's city - you can walk through the Roman theater and conquer the fortress of the crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
A carefully renovated theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, a word.
