Poland and cosmos.
Last week Poland was accepted as a 20th member of this European space agency as a second country from countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of the ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the years thereafter participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
For example, I will mention a lecture by A. Sternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on 6 December 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work Entrance to Astronautism.
The ideas of a young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Award for Entrance to Cosmic Science in France.
The recalled Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautism.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-famous promoter of cosmonautics and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named by his name.
Already in 1925 a rolling dressine was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should have been used to start the dressage or to brake it.
Information about this dressine is only known from the period print.
From 1933 with missile missiles began to occupy the Polish artillery.
The research was provided by Komórka Techniki Urmaenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfek and Prof. Gustawe Mokrzyckiegi.
From preserved materials, it is clear that research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, the arrival of German troops was interrupted by research.
In 1937 a design of a photoelectric fighter rocket was made in professional print by engineer Rohoziński and in the following year the work of Rakiet - torpedo powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza by Leliwa-Krzywoblocký was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all the projects of military use of rocket technology were addressed by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity its activities ended the start of the war.
Further work on cosmonautism appears in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of Polish astronaut society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a reference to the company in the November edition of the 1954 issue of Problemy, in which there are four more extensive articles devoted to astronautism.
In one of them, by Prof. M. Subotowice, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with cosmonautism.
By that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronaut Society (PTA) has tried to join the International Astronaut Federation (founded 1951) and already in autumn, PTA became a full member.
And in the following year, the first Chairman of the PTA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became Vice-President of the International Astronaut Federation.
He held this post until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been significantly involved in the development of a very successful weather rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first start took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a range of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later an improved version of RM-1A was built and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of two-stage RM-2 rockets were launched in the Bledov desert.
The rocket was 1.4 metres long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
Another development type should have been able to really scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have reached 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high wind.
However, further developments were suspended in 1962.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965 became the successor of the first RM rocket.
The rocket was designed as two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32,5 kg.
Three types (marked Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) have been developed which differed in size of space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket there was a 0.4 litre space, a 0.34 litre meteor-1B and a 0.62 litre Meteor-1C.
Maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket development took place at the Aerospace Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a start weight of 380 kg and was able to carry out a useful load of 10 kg up to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later are still to be mentioned.
Poland was also involved in space research in the Intercosmos programme on Soviet artificial satellites and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
