In Iran, Debakl contributed significantly to the loss of Jimmy Carter and Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film directed by Ben Affleck Argo describes an episode of the history that brought America a small victory.
Just before the embassy was filled, six employees fled.
After complex peripetia, they ended up in the Canadian ambassador's residence.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helped with an extravagant cover story - they went to Canada's passports as members of the film crew, who was in the country looking at locations for the filming of a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert on "exfiltrating" Tony Mendez also required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the legend credible, it was written about a film project in specialized magazines, there were press conferences, a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have been classified for a long time, the film is based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is a special combination of multiple genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller, at the same time called "caper movie," the story of a successful piece, a betrayal - an example can be a series of Danny's partners.
In the film, moods take turns - on one side, documented sequences from Tehran (in the subtitle sequence iconic contemporary photos of events and the way in which the same situations were presented in the film are shown - there are no big differences).
On the other hand lightened passages from Hollywood, negotiated with irony and mild exaggeration.
And then the scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, in the hallways of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck's career rebooted in a remarkable way.
He became a respected director of a ridiculous actor, and even his acting stopped being the subject of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after the dark crime of Gone Baby Gone (2007) and thriller City (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film that doesn't take place in the director's home Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that elevated the director's older films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck is also showing it in Argo, where Tehran is playing Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of real events - the opening sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and inquisitiveness that occur when history moves somewhere out of the blue.
Affleck and his co-workers achieve similar effects in stage fiction (false crew on Tehran bazaar).
Too many events in too many places
The director had to deal with the fact that the story doesn't actually offer much in the movie sense of exciting scenes.
