Szabo: "The Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in deciding on the adoption of Palestine.
According to an expert on relations between the US and Europe, Stephen Szaboa is balancing Berlin on the narrow edge of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: Germany first indicated at the beginning of the week that it would vote against the proposal for the observer status of the Palestinians in the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
But now Germany must be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think they're gonna support America's position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without, of course, being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in setting up a no-fly zone.
It was finally pushed through by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on serious international issues?
Yes, it is.
The reason for this is that it is changing its foreign policy, in the direction of the US-led policy, so to speak, towards German foreign policy.
The situation is all the more difficult that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans are between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still settling in, but they're on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, as they do in France or the UK.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean in German terms?
It shows the readiness to take positions that are independent of US or European partners in the event of national interests.
I think German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. exports and its relations with certain areas, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to some extent different from the economic interests of other powers, and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did economic interests have an impact on the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
Firstly, Germany has large outlets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it must be careful not to frighten the public but the elites in Arab countries.
Anyway, that's a big deal.
But I wouldn't want to attribute too much importance to it, it's not exactly a one-sided relationship.
However, this plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany's relations with the US been damaged when Germany abstained from voting in the case of both important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I think there is a great deal of understanding for the German position in Europe and even in the US.
That's why I don't think it was as dramatic a break as it was on Libya.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect from this.
This signals that they must be considered as international players and their interests must be taken into account.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
On the other hand, the US has made itself clear to the veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These differences have always existed as a result of America's internal policy.
I think that Obama's government may have a very strong understanding of the European position in secret.
But as a result of the political situation there, this position cannot, of course, be held publicly.
I think that differences in opinion really aren't as big as they always seem.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama isn't very happy about Netanyahu's politics at all.
Is it not difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's exactly what makes it hard for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and unified European policy, which is currently not happening.
Thus, they cannot be part of a wider line and must instead move things forward from their own position.
That's what they do with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take a leading role in the future and push Europe towards a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, even because of its relationship with Israel.
That's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player? Does it even want to take the lead?
Or is Germany's leading role still difficult?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable, and for obvious reasons it is still difficult to play a larger role for this country.
For example, when we look at the European crisis, whenever Germany takes a greater role, anti-German sentiments arise.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
It's actually an old problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be acceptable to all kinds of neighbors and opinions, and it is not easy.
The US's influence in European politics is now constantly falling, but the EU is currently not filling this vacuum.
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it makes them uncomfortable and makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and politicians from Europe and North America study together the challenges of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Szabo is a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
