What is private offline is private and online
Privacy.
According to the dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something that has a personal nature or "a private life area that everyone has the right to protect against any disruption. "
What is privacy for a man under 16 years of age?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he's posting matters on the Internet that he certainly wouldn't tell anyone during normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between 10 and 15 who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy as "completely own" in a personal way and as "user name and password" when it came to social networks.
"I wouldn't publish my biggest secrets," says ten-year-old Jorge in an attempt to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They are very secret secrets, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
"I put nice photos or pictures of us playing on the FB.
I'm also talking to friends there.
I wouldn't share a picture that wasn't mine, or a picture that would mock someone," he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or write humiliating or gross comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on the FB and his nine Twitter supporters.
Most of them are related.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I set up an account on Twitter to express my views and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone will answer, I'm just putting them there," he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicate with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended someone unknown.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks and at the last mentioned network admits that he does not know 20 people from his list of friends.
"I am not afraid because we have something in common, such as music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them put him up to anything or asked him for an address or phone number.
"If they urge me or require me to do so, I simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José applied to Ask after reading his Twitter recommendation.
This boy is not a stranger to experience what is now called cyberbullying (cybershikana).
"A friend of mine was being blackmailed on social media.
They threatened him and asked for money.
He never knew who he was," he confirms.
According to Jose, the victim didn't check out of his account.
"She just activated the private regime."
Then explains a series of steps to safely set up the account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would publish photos of acquaintances in unpleasant or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I'd do it if I didn't mind or if I just felt like it.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English and a graduate of education and teaching, considers that children and adolescents in social networks need to understand that the main objective of these networks is to inform them.
It states: "The Internet was created as a means of finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed. "
Marrielos Porras notes that an academic worker named Marc Prensky, a graduate of teaching at Yale University and the author of the article Digital natives and digital immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain this phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born during this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and yet we are learning ourselves," he says.
It explains that this is a difficult subject, "because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet mature. "
Also, to be - as far as surroundings are concerned - discreet, at a time when what they desire most is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is is, asking questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do anything doesn't work," he adds.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the options: Are there things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why are you doing it on the Internet?
Or, "Would you like it if someone posted your picture the way you posted your friend's picture?"
Do you know what other people are publishing about you?
When you refer to the person in the photos of the party, did you ask these persons for permission?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you're doing all the time?
The next point is to make them realize that they have to behave in the environment of the Internet as well as outside of it.
It's the same rules.
"A person outside the Internet is governed by respect, morality and other principles, and the same should be done on social networks," he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, a first-level teacher, and an educational counselor explains that it is essential for parents to read the rules of social networking carefully.
"If they understand every sneaky thing, they have a good basis to talk to children about the consequences that an Internet account can have.
For example, as regards age or what is allowed to share or publish," he says.
Guardia is of the opinion that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional "do not talk to strangers" rule.
