AIDS victims today are the result of a late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when the result of his test was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was as if lightning had struck me," he relates in the memory of the moment of truth that the doctor tried to "a little lessen" but apparently without success.
The boy kept it a secret from his family.
He decided to take his own disease on his own, and he started to find out about it, with such commitment that he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the most recent HIV units in the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara (HCG), which he came to in 1994 after several fights with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since the age of 22, which was something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and greater stigma.
At that time, even the director of the Mexican Social Security Institute (IMSS) did not say goodbye to him, "because he had a cut. "
At the time, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are a lot of people who don't know about their disease and who are losing it when the virus has caused the body to destroy and has exhausted the immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years after AIDS disease or at least the first documented cases occurred in the world, "is a great success that the life expectancy of a patient who starts treatment in a timely and appropriate manner is exactly the same as that of healthy people " said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at Guadalajara Civil Hospital, with this information being confirmed in a prestigious scientific publication this April.
Infectologist and HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that scientists have come to the conclusion that since 2008 AIDS has not been a death sentence, but that the duration of survival and full life depends on the degree of disability in the immune system of patients diagnosed with the disease, while those who do not use drugs are better off: people with 200 CD4 cells can live for up to 30 years and people with 500 CD4 cells for up to 50 years.
To put it simply, the person who is diagnosed with HIV at 25 years of age can "live without problems until 75 years of age " according to these findings.
To highlight this progress, it should be recalled that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has decreased significantly in recent years and, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died of AIDS decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4862 in 2011 (UN/AIDS - UNAIDS Joint Programme yearbook), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since AIDS was discovered according to national statistics.
Only in the state of Jalisco, 255 people died in 2011, and by May this year, so far 187. However, universal access to antiretrovirals has been ensured since 2005.
Why do people continue to die from disease?
- "It seems to me that the problem is not in access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how it happens in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years, we have not exhausted the supply of medicines. The problem is that patients come at a very advanced stage because they do not know the state of the disease, or in the late stage of the disease."
It adds a convincing figure: "Nine out of ten patients come when an associated infection has already occurred. All we need to do to influence the overall mortality is to diagnose the disease earlier and therefore to offer large-scale tests for the detection of the disease to all those who ask for it. "
In his proposal, he agrees with specialists and officials from the State AIDS Prevention Council in Jalisco and directly with patients such as Fabrizio, who came to be tested in a private laboratory just because it was done by his friend, and despite his low age, he had already developed AIDS disease and also suffered from Kaposi' sarcoma, a cancer that is one of the usual complications.
"Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're gonna die, and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm gonna die, I'd rather go out three times a week," they say, but that's not my case.
Change was for the better, healthy eating, practicing, taking medication."
To this day, his parents know only that he suffered from cancer.
"I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I look out for myself and for the other person," says Fabrizio, who has accepted the call to share his experience with the MILENIO JALISCO daily to motivate those who are afraid to testify today on World AIDS Day.
"Let them get tested, if they risked it, let them know if they're HIV positive, it's better, and if they've already been diagnosed, no matter how much they realize they can live like anyone else if they're responsible."
This message summarizes the motto of the battle against AIDS this year 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a big gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guatemalan journalist who is researching information on HIV.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places dedicated to this "really increased condom handing out, used to give us one or two, today they give us packages and hundreds of condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who do not have access to condoms," he said.
Among the most susceptible to new infections are adolescents.
"What do you want it for?" is a common question full of irony and assessment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacies and medical staff who want to avoid teenagers, says the reporter.
He proposed to change this ineffective distribution, let the condoms not only be behind the counters, but let the hundred be found in the dispensers in the public bathrooms, in places where the young often go.
"It's not support for promiscuity.
It's not even about paying them a beer and a motel, how Governor Emilio González responded to the question of whether he would agree to distribute condoms in his district.
There is no such sexuality. It is best to make condoms available to those who have already led sexual life," he remarked.
Key numbers in the state of Jalisco
13 435 cases (12 158 cases of AIDS and 1 317 cases of HIV) were reported.
This is the fourth place in Mexico in new and identified cases of AIDS and the 13th place in connection with HIV.
92% of the infection occurs by sexual route, 6% by blood route y 2% perinatally.
It is estimated that about 50,000 people can live with HIV, since there are four to five people who do not know about the disease on one registered case.
The judgment approved by the United States Court of Appeal, which does not recognise the restructuring of Grupo Vitro's debt by a bankruptcy in Mexico, gives an unfortunate precedent for any national enterprise with branches in a neighbouring country and a solvency problem.
Thus, the restructuring procedures of firms that allow Mexican laws do not appear to apply in the country of stripes and stars despite international agreements.
The approval of the judgment issued on 15 June last year by Judge Harlin Hale at the bankruptcy court for North Texas leaves, in practice, Mexican companies without defence against the possibility of confiscating their assets on the other side of the river el Bravo.
However, the judgment opens the door to the United States Supreme Court for the main Mexican glass producer, referring to three irregularities.
It must be said, first of all, that while the judge of this case claims that creditors are to be governed by the United States insolvency law, the Fifth District Court of Appeal, based in New Orleans, says that the main procedure provides for bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
Firstly, this would indicate the ignorance of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinationals.
In essence, a United Nations model law was created for this purpose to unify international commercial law, which is determined by an arbiter by the American Law Institute.
Secondly, the judgment states that without the vote of branches from the internal corporate structure, when Vitro's parent company's debt to branches is recognised, the required majority would not be reached to approve the restructuring.
However, Mexican laws allow this possibility.
The fact is that Vitro's case was not the first in which this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, such as Agremex and Comercial Mexico, for whose in-house debts the Federal Bankruptcy Institute has guaranteed.
Furthermore, it is true that even after deduction of the votes of the branches, creditors - who stood against Vitro in court in the United States, i.e. the "dup" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convertencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not reach the majority.
In the vote, they would have reached about 45 percent to 37.
This figure is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
From another point of view, Vitro blames the difficult situation that it has faced since 2008 - against the backdrop of a serious economic crisis that has struck the United States.
In the meantime, the family company González Sady will appeal for a new assessment directly at the appeal court in order for the assessment to take place with full participation, i.e. with the participation of five judges, because initially only three voted.
If he fails here, he will demand, as an appeal, a revision of the process by a higher instance, in this case by the United States Supreme Court.
The case is serious because the court forgot the document sent by the Mexican Government as an amicus curiae, in which Vitro's procedure under the Competition Act is described in detail, pointing out that the company has made it easier by leaning towards agreements signed by both countries to confront the law in question with Chapter 15 of the United States insolvency law.
Moreover, it is pointed out that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission for International Trade, i.e. rules for international insolvency cases that guarantee equality for debtors and creditors.
Impact on both sides: punishment for both Vitro and the State.
